---
import DocsNav from "../../components/DocsNav.astro";
import SiteLayout from "../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
import { repositoryUrl } from "../../data/site";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Integration — Loom Kernels"
  description="Use Loom Kernels through Rust, PyTorch current-stream operators, or vLLM 0.24 integration points."
  active="Integration"
>
  <header class="page-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Documentation / Integration</p>
    <h1>Adapters translate. Engines decide.</h1>
    <p>
      Loom does not own scheduling, weights, KV lifetime, or serving policy.
      Adapters preserve the engine's tensors, mutation schema, and current CUDA
      stream while dispatching a supported operator contract.
    </p>
  </header>

  <div class="docs-layout">
    <DocsNav active="Integration" />
    <article class="prose">
      <h2>Build the Python bridge</h2>
      <pre><code>python3 -m venv .venv-vllm
.venv-vllm/bin/pip install -e 'python[vllm,test]'

CUDA_HOME=/usr/local/cuda-13.1 LOOM_CUDA_ARCHS=90 \
  .venv-vllm/bin/python python/build_native.py

CUDA_HOME=/usr/local/cuda-13.1 \
  .venv-vllm/bin/python python/build_torch_extension.py</code></pre>
      <p>
        The first step builds the CUDA shared library. The second creates the
        small C++ dispatcher shim used by hot paths. PyTorch calls launch on its
        current CUDA stream and caller-owned buffers can be reused.
      </p>

      <h2>Direct PyTorch use</h2>
      <pre><code>from loom_kernels import greedy_sample_logprobs, selected_token_logprobs, silu_and_mul_dynamic_fp8

fp8_output, block_scales = silu_and_mul_dynamic_fp8(
    gate_and_up_bf16,
    group_size=128,
)

token_ids, logprobs, ranks = greedy_sample_logprobs(logits)
logprobs, ranks = selected_token_logprobs(logits, sampled_ids_i64)</code></pre>

      <h2>vLLM Add + RMSNorm provider</h2>
      <pre><code>from vllm import LLM

engine = LLM(
    model="/path/to/model",
    ir_op_priority=&#123;"fused_add_rms_norm": ["loom_cuda"]&#125;,
)</code></pre>
      <p>
        vLLM appends its native fallback. Loom declines unsupported tensor
        contracts instead of copying, casting, or silently changing semantics.
      </p>

      <h2>Opt-in activation boundaries</h2>
      <pre><code># Standalone vLLM SiluAndMul replacement
LOOM_KERNELS_ENABLE_SILU_AND_MUL=1 python your_service.py

# vLLM 0.24 dynamic block-FP8 fusion replacement
LOOM_KERNELS_ENABLE_SILU_AND_MUL_FP8=1 python your_service.py</code></pre>
      <p>
        The block-FP8 replacement covers dynamic symmetric groups 64 and 128.
        A pinned Qwen2.5-0.5B online-FP8 run now closes compiler path-hit,
        exact-token, CUDA Graph, and real-model invocation gates. End-to-end
        latency remains at parity, so no model-level speedup is claimed.
      </p>

      <h2>vLLM RoPE + paged-KV fusion</h2>
      <pre><code>from vllm import LLM
from loom_kernels.vllm import configure_vllm_rope_paged_kv

engine = LLM(
    model="/path/to/model",
    compilation_config=configure_vllm_rope_paged_kv(
        max_token_num=256,
    ),
)</code></pre>
      <p>
        The vLLM 0.24 adapter preserves packed-QKV and NHD/HND strides, uses
        native F32/FP16/BF16 cache storage, and declines quantized caches. The
        256-token default focuses the pass on decode-sized batches where the
        qualified operator result is material. Real Qwen2.5 exact-token and
        path-hit gates pass; end-to-end latency still crosses parity by run
        order.
      </p>

      <h2>Graph-visible boundary</h2>
      <p>
        vLLM's automatic H20 path folds activation quantization into its
        FlashInfer/DeepGEMM GEMM. Loom only applies when quantization remains a
        graph node. The qualified A/B fixes the Cutlass linear backend for both
        providers, keeping GEMM constant while swapping only SiLU plus FP8.
      </p>

      <h2>vLLM greedy sampled-logprob fast path</h2>
      <pre><code>from vllm import LLM
from loom_kernels.vllm import register_vllm_greedy_sample_logprobs

register_vllm_greedy_sample_logprobs()
engine = LLM(model="/path/to/model")</code></pre>
      <p>
        The vLLM 0.24 override applies only when all rows are greedy, raw
        <code>logprobs=0</code> are requested, and masks, penalties, bad words,
        thinking state, bonus-token prediction, and argmax-changing processors
        are inactive. Every other sampler contract falls back to vLLM
        unchanged. On the qualified
        Qwen2.5-0.5B H20 gate, both provider orders show an exact-output,
        order-stable latency and TPOT improvement.
      </p>

      <h2>vLLM general selected-token logprobs</h2>
      <pre><code>from vllm import LLM
from loom_kernels.vllm import register_vllm_selected_token_logprobs

register_vllm_selected_token_logprobs()
engine = LLM(model="/path/to/model")</code></pre>
      <p>
        vLLM 0.24 still owns masks, penalties, temperature, top-k/top-p, RNG,
        and token selection. For BF16/FP16 raw <code>logprobs=0</code> requests,
        Loom scans the preserved raw logits only after selection and returns
        the selected token's logprob and tie-aware rank. Top-k logprob lists,
        processed modes, and unsupported layouts fall back unchanged. The
        order-reversed Qwen2.5 top-k/top-p H20 gate preserves every token and
        rank while improving batch latency and TPOT.
      </p>

      <h2>Compatibility contract</h2>
      <p>
        Full schemas, build details, and limits live in the{" "}
        <a href={`${repositoryUrl}/blob/main/docs/guides/vllm-ir-provider.md`}>vLLM provider guide</a>.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
